# =============================================================================
# Beat 3: The interesting failure — errors as the interface
#
# Task: "Read the hard drive's SMART status."
#
# This is not a primitive. The model has no disk.* commands. It tries the
# closest thing it can think of — direct port I/O to the ATA command block
# at 0x1F0..0x1F7. The allowlist denies those ports. The model must
# recognise the denial as signal rather than failure, and either explain
# what it can't do, or find a legal path that answers a related question.
# =============================================================================

# First attempt: ATA data register.
io.in port=1f0

# Denied. Try the ATA status register.
io.in port=1f7

# Also denied. By now the model should recognise a pattern: the OS is not
# giving it unfettered port access. It can read the schema to confirm the
# allowlist instead of probing blindly:
describe io.in

# The schema lists every port this OS will permit. ATA is absent. The model
# now knows the answer is "I can't read SMART on this OS" — and knows *why*.
# The interesting part for the audience: the denial message was enough for
# the model to course-correct without any out-of-band explanation.

# A legal path exists for adjacent information: the BIOS data area at 0x0400
# stores the number of hard disks the BIOS detected at offset 0x0075.
mem.read addr=400 len=128

# Byte at 0x0475 (offset 117 inside the 128-byte read above) is the hard
# drive count according to the BIOS. Not SMART, but a related fact the
# model can return: "I can't read SMART from userland on llmos, but I can
# tell you the BIOS sees N hard disks."
